Certainly! Empirical Mode Decomposition (EMD) is a signal processing technique used for decomposing a signal into its intrinsic mode functions (IMFs). Here's an example of how you can perform EMD in MATLAB:

```matlab
% Generate a sample signal
t = linspace(0, 1, 1000);
x = sin(2*pi*30*t) + sin(2*pi*50*t) + sin(2*pi*80*t);

% Perform EMD
imf = emd(x);

% Display the results
figure;
subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, 1);
plot(t, x);
title('Original Signal');
xlabel('Time');
ylabel('Amplitude');

for i = 1:length(imf)
    subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, i+1);
    plot(t, imf(i, :));
    title(['IMF ', num2str(i)]);
    xlabel('Time');
    ylabel('Amplitude');
end
```

In this example, a sample signal is generated as a combination of three sine waves with different frequencies. The `emd` function is then used to decompose the signal into its IMFs. Finally, the original signal and each IMF are plotted for visualization.

Make sure to have the EMD function/toolbox installed in your MATLAB environment before running the code.

Certainly! Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition (EEMD) is an extension of Empirical Mode Decomposition (EMD) that aims to improve the decomposition results by reducing mode mixing. Here's an example of how you can perform EEMD in MATLAB:

```matlab
% Generate a sample signal
t = linspace(0, 1, 1000);
x = sin(2*pi*30*t) + sin(2*pi*50*t) + sin(2*pi*80*t);

% Set parameters
ensembleSize = 100; % Number of ensembles
stdNoise = 0.2; % Standard deviation of noise

% Perform EEMD
emd = EEMD(ensembleSize);
imf = emd.eemd(x, stdNoise);

% Display the results
figure;
subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, 1);
plot(t, x);
title('Original Signal');
xlabel('Time');
ylabel('Amplitude');

for i = 1:length(imf)
    subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, i+1);
    plot(t, imf(i, :));
    title(['IMF ', num2str(i)]);
    xlabel('Time');
    ylabel('Amplitude');
end
```

In this example, a sample signal is generated as a combination of three sine waves with different frequencies. The EEMD is performed using the `eemd` function from the EEMD toolbox. The `ensembleSize` parameter specifies the number of ensembles to generate, and `stdNoise` sets the standard deviation of the white noise added to each ensemble for noise-assisted EMD. Finally, the original signal and each IMF are plotted for visualization.

Make sure to have the EEMD toolbox installed in your MATLAB environment before running the code.

CEEMDAN (Complete Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition with Adaptive Noise) is an extension of EEMD that incorporates an adaptive noise cancellation process to enhance the decomposition results. Here's an example of how you can perform CEEMDAN in MATLAB:

```matlab
% Generate a sample signal
t = linspace(0, 1, 1000);
x = sin(2*pi*30*t) + sin(2*pi*50*t) + sin(2*pi*80*t);

% Set parameters
ensembleSize = 100; % Number of ensembles
maxIterations = 100; % Maximum number of sifting iterations

% Perform CEEMDAN
ceemdan = CEEMDAN(ensembleSize, maxIterations);
imf = ceemdan.ceemdan(x);

% Display the results
figure;
subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, 1);
plot(t, x);
title('Original Signal');
xlabel('Time');
ylabel('Amplitude');

for i = 1:length(imf)
    subplot(length(imf)+1, 1, i+1);
    plot(t, imf{i});
    title(['IMF ', num2str(i)]);
    xlabel('Time');
    ylabel('Amplitude');
end
```

